<div id="law-category-modal" class="law-category-modal">
    <div class="law-category-modal-content">
        <h2>Law Categories</h2>
        <ol>
            <li><strong>Agrarian Reform Law:</strong> Covers the redistribution of agricultural land, land tenure improvements, and support for rural development and farmers' welfare.</li>
            <li><strong>Alternative Dispute Resolution (ADR) Law:</strong> Encompasses the legal processes of resolving disputes through methods like mediation, arbitration, and conciliation instead of traditional court trials.</li>
            <li><strong>Aviation Law:</strong> Governs the operation of aircraft, air traffic control, aviation safety standards, licensing, and the rights and responsibilities of passengers and operators.</li>
            <li><strong>Bankruptcy Law:</strong> Provides procedures for individuals or businesses to discharge their debts or reorganize financial obligations under the supervision of a court.</li>
            <li><strong>Civil Litigation Law:</strong> Covers the processes by which legal disputes between private parties are resolved through lawsuits in civil courts, including damages, injunctions, and breach of contract cases.</li>
            <li><strong>Constitutional Law:</strong> Defines the framework of a country's government structure, powers, and the fundamental rights of citizens as protected by the constitution.</li>
            <li><strong>Corporate Law:</strong> Regulates the creation, governance, operations, mergers, acquisitions, and dissolution of corporations, as well as corporate responsibility and shareholder rights.</li>
            <li><strong>Criminal Law:</strong> Specifies offenses against the state or public, detailing the punishment for actions deemed harmful to society, including crimes such as theft, assault, and murder.</li>
            <li><strong>Cybersecurity and Data Privacy Law:</strong> Protects data from cyber threats, ensures data privacy rights, and regulates the handling, storage, and sharing of personal and sensitive information by organizations.</li>
            <li><strong>Education Law:</strong> Governs the educational system, covering school administration, student rights, teacher qualifications, educational standards, and policies related to access and equality in education.</li>
            <li><strong>Election Law:</strong> Regulates the electoral process, including voter eligibility, election procedures, campaign finance, and the rights of candidates and voters during elections.</li>
            <li><strong>Energy Law:</strong> Encompasses the regulation of energy resources, including the exploration, production, distribution, and consumption of energy, as well as renewable energy policies and regulations.</li>
            <li><strong>Entertainment and Media Law:</strong> Covers intellectual property rights, contracts, and regulatory matters in the entertainment and media industries, including film, television, music, and digital content.</li>
            <li><strong>Environmental Law:</strong> Addresses the protection of the environment through regulations on pollution, conservation, natural resource management, climate change, and sustainability.</li>
            <li><strong>Family Law:</strong> Covers legal matters relating to family relationships, including marriage, divorce, child custody, adoption, and the distribution of marital property.</li>
            <li><strong>Financial Services and Securities Law:</strong> Regulates the financial markets, securities trading, investment banking, insurance, and consumer protection in the financial industry.</li>
            <li><strong>Health Care Law:</strong> Governs the delivery of health care services, including the rights of patients, medical professionals, health insurance policies, and the regulation of health care institutions.</li>
            <li><strong>Human Rights Law:</strong> Protects the fundamental rights and freedoms of individuals, ensuring equality and justice through laws against discrimination, torture, and violations of civil liberties.</li>
            <li><strong>Immigration Law:</strong> Regulates the entry, stay, and removal of foreign nationals, including visa issuance, citizenship, asylum, and deportation processes.</li>
            <li><strong>Insurance Law:</strong> Governs the regulation of insurance companies and policies, addressing coverage, claims, premiums, and the rights of policyholders and insurers.</li>
            <li><strong>Intellectual Property Law:</strong> Protects creations of the mind, including patents, copyrights, trademarks, and trade secrets, by regulating their use, protection, and licensing.</li>
            <li><strong>International Law:</strong> Governs the relationships between sovereign nations and international entities, including treaties, human rights conventions, conflict resolution, and international trade.</li>
            <li><strong>Labor Law:</strong> Covers the rights and duties of employers and employees, including work conditions, wages, benefits, collective bargaining, and workplace safety.</li>
            <li><strong>Maritime Law:</strong> Regulates shipping, navigation, and activities on the seas, including shipping contracts, maritime accidents, and international maritime treaties.</li>
            <li><strong>Public Interest Law:</strong> Focuses on legal practices that serve the public good, particularly in areas of social justice, civil rights, environmental protection, and advocacy for marginalized groups.</li>
            <li><strong>Real Estate Law:</strong> Governs the buying, selling, leasing, and development of property, including land use, zoning, construction, and property rights.</li>
            <li><strong>Tax Law:</strong> Regulates the collection, assessment, and enforcement of taxes by government authorities, covering income, property, sales, and other types of taxation.</li>
            <li><strong>Trade and Customs Law:</strong> Regulates international trade by establishing rules for tariffs, import/export laws, trade agreements, and customs procedures for goods crossing borders.</li>
        </ol>        
    </div>
